WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.780
So Arlo, Captogen, Autolucil, this is our first GPRC5D-directed CAR-T cell therapy that

00:00:05.780 --> 00:00:07.620
is being looked at in clinic already.

00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:12.600
So this is a great paper, a presentation that's about to be a paper hopefully soon that Doris

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:15.280
Hansen presented at the last ASH.

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:18.460
And it's just looking at those patients who are quad exposed now.

00:00:18.460 --> 00:00:21.540
And this was flat iron and just saying, you know, what are patients getting?

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.720
And again, most patients are getting chemotherapy at this point.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:28.860
There are some patients that have gotten GPRC5D by specifics, as you can tell.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.080
But in majority, these patients don't have a great response or PFS or survival.

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:36.580
13.4 months is what's considered.

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:39.820
Again, these patients had CAR-Ts as well as BCMA by specifics.

00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:43.760
But post-BCMA, this is the unmet need in our patient population.

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:50.180
So again, it's a CAR-T autologous against GPRC5D, which we know is on malignant plasma

00:00:50.180 --> 00:00:54.820
cells, a little bit different than BCMA that we don't really see it on B cells or, you

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:55.940
know, more premature cells.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:59.020
And there is a little bit more loss of GPRC5D.

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:02.380
It seems a little bit more like CD19 than it does BCMA.

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:05.600
So this was the phase one study design.

00:01:05.740 --> 00:01:10.420
Susan Ball presented this data, I think, last IMS was the most updated.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:15.220
And then she also presented a poster on patients in the first one to three lines.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.200
So the original study did require three prior lines of therapy.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:20.980
Patients could have or could not have had BCMA therapy.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:24.580
So that's sort of how they presented that data in here.

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:28.920
And again, most of these patients, bridging therapy was optional, a little bit over half

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:29.020
PPS.

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:29.920
The patients got it.

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:33.520
And time for infusion was about 19 days from bridging.

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:35.080
Then the results.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:37.640
So again, response rates were pretty fantastic.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.240
Sorry, my slides didn't show the actual numbers up there.

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:45.640
But 94% overall response rate in those patients that are early line, so one to three prior

00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:50.500
lines, 91% to 92% for those who are on late line, greater than three prior lines.

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:55.120
This was at the RP2D dosing, which was considered 150 million cells at the time.

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:58.160
And then CRR in early line has actually been 71%.

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:03.940
Again, median PFS in that early line cohort, again, was presented at IMS was 24.3 months.

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.360
And then because of the toxicity.

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:11.180
So most of these toxicities, cytopenias, et cetera, we know how to take care of.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:18.480
However, GPRC5D, of course, we know there's a specific skin, scusia type stuff.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:23.860
We see it less compared to the bispecifics and not 100% sure if it's just because it's

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:24.620
not as continuous.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:26.320
Patients can get it.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:28.660
But usually if they get it, it goes away after the first.

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:29.400
Two to three months.

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:31.640
And a lot of our patients haven't gotten it.

00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:33.480
However, there's a new neurotoxicity.

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:37.500
So we're putting our neurologists, you know, their thinking hats on.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:40.720
So there's a different toxicity that we see with ataxia.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:43.520
I forgot what we called it now.

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:49.820
But basically, with the study, we're calling it ONS or other neurotoxic selected OSN, other

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:51.060
selected neurotoxicities.

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:52.760
And again, it's more cerebellum.

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:55.540
And it has to do with maybe GPRC5D being there.

00:02:55.540 --> 00:02:57.540
There are some patients with the bispecifics.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:02.360
You know, maybe one to two years later that I've had that also get this ataxia cerebellar

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:02.640
syndrome.

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:04.440
So definitely very important.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:10.020
So this was why the next studies have all actually decreased the dose of the cells from

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:11.140
150 to 75.

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:16.160
So all the other data down the road, we'll see what happens at the 75 million cell dose.

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:17.180
And I think that's really important.

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.580
We know that relapsed refractory patients, their T cells are different versus early line.

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:24.840
They're very, the microenvironment, the T cells, everything's very, very different.

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:28.280
And maybe cell dosing needs to be different based on when you're treating those patients.

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:29.400
So we'll see.

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:32.160
We'll see if that helps and works out with these studies.

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:36.240
So then there's the quintessential phase two study that is ongoing right now.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:39.800
And again, most of these patients got 150 million cells.

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:45.040
And there's now a cohort that's getting 75 million, again, just to look at toxicity

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:46.000
versus efficacy.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:52.080
In the phase one, 75 million and 150 actually did relatively similarly in their both CR

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:53.680
rates as well as overall response rate.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:56.660
So hopefully we'll have some data soon in the next year.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:58.260
I'm hoping by 2026.

00:03:58.260 --> 00:04:00.640
I don't know yet, but I'm hoping very soon.

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:06.080
And then of course, the ongoing is the phase three study that they have looking at standard

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:11.320
of care versus Arlo cell at the 75 million, that lower dose.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:16.860
And this is against Darapomdax versus a carfilzomib based regimen as a standard of care.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:22.320
And again, it started about a year ago and hopefully in the next couple of years, we'll

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:26.540
have some results from earlier line and this does not require BCMA therapy.

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:28.240
So what I forgot to say is a phase two.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:30.380
It does require prior BCMA therapy.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:33.380
So that will be in patients who are post BCMA here.

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:35.980
They'll look at patients who have had BCMA versus not.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:38.480
So here's that development roadmap.

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:40.100
Now with that, just conclusions.

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:43.220
I think it's a really important target in myeloma.

00:04:43.580 --> 00:04:45.920
There are other studies being looked at in combination.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:46.860
I won't talk about that.

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:48.740
I think the next session we'll talk about combinations.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:56.560
And so again, as a single agent seems to have pretty significant response as well as a toxicity

00:04:56.560 --> 00:04:58.220
in general has been pretty significant.

00:04:58.280 --> 00:05:02.340
It's pretty easy to take care of these patients, but that neurotox is really important.

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:05.600
And what we have learned, which I can't share yet, but there are some translational data,

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:09.360
hopefully coming soon, the better bridging you have, the less likely these patients get

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:10.360
this.

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:15.960
And so coming back to my usual discussion of bridging therapy for our first line, our

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:20.880
first CAR Ts that have come out, we really need bridging for these patients.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:23.940
We'll see if the next CAR Ts we don't, and we'll talk about that probably a little bit

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:24.740
later today.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:25.700
So thank you.
